"recipe.be_lapin_a_la_gueuze.drink.body" = "Pair with gueuze itself or another dry, tart lambic-style beer that mirrors the sauce’s bright acidity. A light-bodied red such as Pinot Noir can also work if you prefer wine. For a non-alcoholic option, serve sparkling water or a tart alcohol-free apple drink to match the sweet-sour profile.";
"recipe.be_lapin_a_la_gueuze.drink.summary" = "Beer (Gueuze)";
"recipe.be_lapin_a_la_gueuze.info" = "Lapin à la gueuze is a traditional Brussels and Brabant dish of rabbit pieces browned and then slowly braised in gueuze, the region’s spontaneously fermented beer. The sauce turns deep and tangy, gently balanced with a touch of sugar, aromatics, and mustard, often finished with prunes for a classic sweet-sour note. It is traditionally served hot with Belgian frites and mayonnaise to soak up the distinctive gueuze sauce.";
